    <div class="paragraph1">
        <h2><b>To Kill a Mockingbird</b> by <u>Harper Lee</u></h2>
        <p>
            <i>Tuer un Mockingbird</i> stands as one of the most influential novels in American literature. 
            This masterpiece explores themes of racial injustice, moral growth, and the loss of innocence through 
            the eyes of a young girl named Scout. The narrative brilliantly weaves together coming-of-age elements 
            with a gripping courtroom drama that challenges readers to confront their own prejudices and beliefs.
        </p>
        <div class="quote">
            "You never really understand a person until you consider things from his point of view."
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="paragraph2">
        <h2>A Timeless Narrative</h2>
        <p>
            Lee's prose is elegant and deeply moving, creating unforgettable characters that resonate long after 
            the final page. The novel's exploration of courage—both moral and physical—provides readers with profound 
            lessons about standing up for what is right. For more context on the novel's historical significance, 
            visit <a href="https://www.sparknotes.com/lit/mockingbird/">SparkNotes for additional analysis and text fragments</a>. 
            Whether you're a first-time reader or revisiting this classic, the book offers new insights and reflections 
            on justice, compassion, and human dignity.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="comments-section">
